# {{ project_name }}

Go HTTP producer for the `{{ project_name }}` message group(s). It posts
[CloudEvents](https://cloudevents.io/) to an HTTP endpoint using the
[CloudEvents SDK for Go](https://github.com/cloudevents/sdk-go).

This project was generated with the [xRegistry CLI](https://github.com/xregistry/codegen).

## Layout

- `{{ project_name }}` — this module, the HTTP CloudEvents producer.
- `{{ data_project_name }}` — sibling module with the generated data classes,
  referenced via a `replace` directive in `go.mod`.

## Usage

Create a producer for a message group and send events to a target URL:

```go
package main

import (
	"context"

	producer "{{ project_name | snake }}"
)

func main() {
	p, err := producer.NewYourGroupProducer("https://example.com/events")
	if err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}
	defer p.Close()

	// Optionally switch to CloudEvents HTTP binary content mode.
	// p.SetContentMode(producer.ContentModeBinary)

	ctx := context.Background()
	if err := p.SendYourMessage(ctx, data); err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}
}
```

### Content modes

- `ContentModeStructured` (default) — the whole CloudEvent is serialized as
  `application/cloudevents+json` in the request body.
- `ContentModeBinary` — the event data is the request body and the CloudEvents
  attributes are carried as `ce-*` HTTP headers.

Use `SetContentMode` to select the mode before sending.

### Testing

Each `Send*` method accepts a `context.Context`, so tests can supply an
`httptest.Server` URL as the target and assert against the received request
without a live endpoint. The constructor `New<Group>ProducerWithClient` also
accepts a custom `cloudevents.Client` for injection.

